Story 3: Environment Setup
The application environment is built around a Python virtual environment (venv) containing the web frameworks, database connectors, and AI models required for local development.

1. Core Dependencies
All dependencies are defined in 
requirements.txt
:

fastapi==0.138.1 & uvicorn==0.49.0: Used to build and serve the asynchronous backend REST API.
SQLAlchemy==2.0.51: Serves as the Object-Relational Mapper (ORM) to handle SQLite database integration.
pydantic==2.13.4: Handles data validation and settings management for API payloads.
requests==2.34.2 & Wikipedia-API==0.15.0: Provides HTTP client capabilities to search and query Wikipedia summaries for the fact-checking assistant.
torch==2.12.1 & transformers==5.12.1: Core deep learning frameworks used to load distilbert-base-uncased and gpt2 locally.
streamlit==1.58.0: Simplifies the creation of the responsive web interface.
pytest==9.1.1: Framework for executing automated unit and integration tests.
2. Local Environment Bootstrapping (Windows)
To set up the development environment from scratch on Windows, execute the following commands in your shell:

Step A: Create and Activate the Virtual Environment
powershell


# Create the virtual environment named 'venv'
python -m venv venv
# Activate the virtual environment
.\venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
Step B: Install Requirements
powershell


# Upgrade pip to the latest version
python -m pip install --upgrade pip
# Install dependencies from requirements.txt
pip install -r backend/requirements.txt
3. Verification & Execution
Once the environment setup is complete, verify that the services load properly by launching the servers in separate terminals (with the virtual environment activated):

Start the Backend API Server:

powershell


.\venv\Scripts\uvicorn backend.main:app --reload
The API will be available at http://127.0.0.1:8000 with interactive docs at /docs.

Start the Frontend UI Client:

powershell


.\venv\Scripts\streamlit run frontend/app.py
The Streamlit web application interface will open in your default browser at http://localhost:8501.